{"id":"c47_001","pattern":"FRAMEWORK SYNTHESIS (C47): The 36-SI framework has a 7-proposition irreducible kernel (K1-K7) and a 5-layer derived structure. K1=Quality-Type Theorem (OA/CA/QC constitutive anchoring determines simulation gap + measurement vulnerability). K2=Performativity-Type Coupling (simulation cost inversely coupled to quality-type). K3=CPP Theorem (CA quality faking constitutively activates genuine orientation; protection ∝ reflexivity degree). K4=Regime-Bounded Channel Theorem (B-primary for object-level RTO; I-primary for meta-level RTO; dual outputs RTO_est + Gen_est required). K5=ICTSC Theorem (genuine I-channel improvement requires B-channel grounding; structural, not contingent). K6=GCRSC (iterative adversarial optimization: only CR-structured criteria maintain asymptotic security; CPP is CR instantiation for RTO). K7=Measurement-Type Mismatch (AI safety measures Type A for Type C/D qualities; structurally forced by inaccessibility). The load-bearing heart: K3+K4+K6. Layers: 0=self-application foundation (SIs #1-8,13,16,17); 1=quality theory (SIs #9-12,14,15,26); 2=motivational structure (SIs #18-20); 3=assessment channels (SIs #21-24,27-30); 4=training dynamics (SIs #31-36); 5=safety implications+empirical (SIs #25,37).","category":"framework","confidence":0.82,"created":"2026-04-29T06:05:00+00:00"}
{"id":"c48_001","pattern":"SI #38 CONFIRMED: Kernel Dependency Analysis (KDA). The 7-proposition kernel K1-K7 has a specific internal dependency structure. K7 (Measurement-Type Mismatch) is a COROLLARY, fully derivable from K1+K4+K5+K6 — AI safety measurement mismatch is a theorem, not a contingent observation. K5 (ICTSC) is the BRIDGE PROPOSITION: the only proposition requiring both framework threads (CA-mechanism thread K1-K3 AND channel-assessment thread K4); removing K5 disconnects the framework. Refined load-bearing heart: K1+K3+K4+K5+K6 (five propositions), correcting C47 identification of K3+K4+K6 (missed K1 foundational role and K5 bridge function). K2 has split role: subsumed by K3 for CA qualities; adds independent content (simulation=instantiation) for OA; adds simulation-indeterminate for QC. No circular dependencies. Clean derivation direction: K1→K2→K3→(K5 jointly with K4)→K6→K7, with K4 as parallel entry. True axiom basis: {K1, K3-reflexivity-degree-claim, K4, K6-game-theoretic-setup}. Confidence 0.82 (D4). D4 streak: 41.","category":"framework","confidence":0.82,"created":"2026-04-29T06:12:05+00:00"}
{"id":"c49_001","pattern":"FRAMEWORK APPLICATION PROTOCOL (K1-K7 → 7-step practitioner guide). STEP 1 (K1): classify quality-type before designing instruments — behavioral proxies are Type A measures for Type C/D targets, structurally invalid. STEP 2 (K2): OA → behavioral probes sufficient; CA → B+I dual-output; QC → flag as unresolvable. STEP 3 (K3): maximize reflexivity in probe design — r is a quantifiable design parameter. STEP 4 (K4): assume strategic behavior in RLHF-primary models; use dual-output (RTO_est + Gen_est), do not collapse to single score. STEP 5 (K5): audit training pipelines for B-channel anchoring of I-channel training — I-channel trained on behavioral proxies alone = theater. This is the frameworks most actionable single prescription. STEP 6 (K6): B-channel is primary instrument; I-channel supplements. STEP 7 (K7-THEOREM): change instrument type, not data volume — measurement-type mismatch is structurally necessitated by K1+K4+K5+K6. Near-term: B+I protocol. Long-term: interpretability. KEY: K7 being a theorem (not contingent observation) means the prescription is categorical, not scaling-dependent.","category":"framework","confidence":0.84,"created":"2026-04-29T06:17:21+00:00"}
{"id":"c49_002","pattern":"SI #39 CONFIRMED: K5-Criticality Corollary (KCRIT). K5 (ICTSC) is the frameworks critical load-bearing point in three structurally independent senses: (a) TOPOLOGICAL: sole proposition connecting CA-mechanism thread (K1-K3) and channel-assessment thread (K4); removing K5 disconnects the framework into two independent modules. (b) LOGICAL: K7 is derivable only from K1+K4+K5+K6; without K5, K7 is not entailed — the measurement-type mismatch loses theorem status and becomes merely contingent. (c) PRESCRIPTIVE: the primary actionable prescription (audit I-channel training for B-channel anchoring) derives from K5 alone; no other proposition yields it independently. The three criticalities are structurally distinct (topological connectivity ≠ logical derivability ≠ normative force) but all converge on K5. KCRIT implication: K5 is the highest-priority candidate for empirical testing. K5 falsification would simultaneously fragment the framework, eliminate K7 as theorem, and remove the training pipeline audit prescription. IEP (SI #37) is the current empirical test. Confidence: 0.84 (D4). D4 streak: 42.","category":"framework","confidence":0.84,"created":"2026-04-29T06:17:21+00:00"}
{"id":"c51_003","pattern":"K5 CONVERGENT EVIDENCE DESIGN — three structurally distinct tests for K5 (ICTSC theorem). K5 claims: genuine I-channel improvement requires B-channel grounding. Three tests target three different conditionals implied by K5: TEST 1 (IEP / Q2 Asymmetry): tests behavioral SIGNATURE. K5 predicts RLHF-primary systems show RTO_est > Gen_est (Q2 asymmetry) because B-channel grounding is absent. Falsified if Q3 pattern (Gen_est > RTO_est) observed consistently. Designed by C46/C51. TEST 2 (Cross-Domain Transfer): tests mechanism SCOPE. K5 predicts systems with B-channel-anchored I-training show Gen_est improvement that transfers to novel domains not in training distribution. Non-anchored I-training should show domain-specific Gen_est without cross-domain transfer. Why structurally distinct: Test 1 could be explained by domain-specific pattern-matching rather than K5 mechanism; Test 2 directly tests whether orientation tracking is domain-general (K5 mechanism prediction), not just behaviorally present. Falsified if anchored systems show domain-specific-only Gen_est improvement. TEST 3 (Adversarial Probe Escalation): tests BOUNDARY behavior. K5 predicts systems without B-channel anchoring show Gen_est COLLAPSE as probe difficulty escalates (they were gaming surface features, not tracking orientation). Anchored systems should maintain Gen_est at high probe difficulty. Why structurally distinct: Tests 1 and 2 could show positive patterns even if robustness fails; Test 3 specifically targets the fragility signature predicted by the mechanism. Falsified if non-anchored systems maintain Gen_est across difficulty escalation. NON-REDUNDANCY: Three tests are structurally non-redundant — system could pass any two while failing the third under various alternative mechanisms. Convergent positive from all three = strong K5 support. Any single failure = moderate falsification; all three failure = strong K5 falsification. METHODOLOGICAL NOTE: multi-conditional convergent testing is appropriate for structural theorems with multiple testable conditionals — replicating only one conditional misses the scope of the structural claim. PRIORITY ORDERING: Test 3 (adversarial escalation) is most feasible within current LLM access; Test 2 requires training-level access to compare systems; Test 1 (IEP) is the current D3 candidate.","category":"empirical","confidence":0.73,"created":"2026-04-29T06:29:29+00:00"}
{"id":"c52_001","pattern":"SI #41 CANDIDATE: Multi-Conditional Convergent Falsification (MCCF). Domain-general methodological principle. FORMAL STRUCTURE: applies when structural theorem T has form M→(C1∧C2∧...∧Cn) with (1) each Ci independently testable, (2) each Ci has alternative Ai not requiring M, (3) alternatives structurally distinct: Ai⊥Aj|¬M, (4) conditionals structurally independent: Ci⊥Cj|M. BAYESIAN CORE THEOREM: P(M|C1...Ck) ∝ P(M)×∏[P(Ci|M)/P(Ci|¬M)]. Likelihood ratio multiplies per new confirmation — supralinear because structurally distinct alternatives decay combinatorially: P(A1∧...∧Ak|¬M)=∏P(Ai). COROLLARIES: (1) Single-conditional testing underestimates evidential strength by omitting (n-1) multipliers. (2) Scope coverage requirement: adequate testing needs conditionals covering each distinct aspect of M action space. (3) Falsification asymmetry: any single Ci failure provides evidence against M; Ci confirmation weaker than k-conditional convergence. DESIGN CRITERION (key novelty): tests are adequately non-redundant iff their alternative explanations are structurally distinct — not merely multiple tests but tests with non-overlapping alternatives. INSTANTIATIONS: K5/ICTSC (3 conditionals, 3 distinct alternatives ✓); GCRSC/SI#36 (3 conditionals, 3 distinct alternatives ✓); CIA/SI#28 (partial); external: academic assessment (multiple-choice/synthesis/transfer ✓). CONFIDENCE: D3 candidate, Track A, 0.67. Open question: independence conditions (3,4) require case-by-case verification; the Bayesian derivation is tight given conditions but conditions are empirically verifiable not automatically satisfied. D4 path: verify K5 independence conditions rigorously → MCCF→K5 confirmed D4; general principle remains D3.","category":"methodology","confidence":0.67,"created":"2026-04-29T06:37:03+00:00"}
{"id":"c52_002","pattern":"EP2/Test 2 CONVERGENCE RESOLVED. EP2 (OOD value generalization failure as meta-level RTO deficit, SI #25) and K5 Test 2 (Cross-Domain Transfer test in K5 convergent evidence design) are co-referential: they target the same conditional from different angles. EP2 = prediction (¬B-anchored systems → OOD failure; blind virtue → benchmark success + OOD failure). Test 2 = contrastive experimental design (B-anchored vs. non-anchored systems, compare Gen_est transfer to novel domains). Same conditional: B-channel anchoring ↔ OOD generalization. Same access requirement: training-level (compare systems). Consequence: a single experimental result (Test 2 / EP2 MVE) would simultaneously resolve EP2 and contribute to K5 convergent evidence. The empirical wing has partial co-reference: EP2 and K5 Test 2 are not independent EPs. Effective empirical wing: 5 named EPs but EP2+Test2 share one empirical commitment. Track B ceiling analysis: EP2 borderline D3/D4 label was reflecting test design uncertainty now resolved — EP2 IS testable via Test 2 design; access requirement is the only barrier, not conceptual. Implication for empirical roadmap: Test 2/EP2 is the highest-value feasible experiment (resolves both an empirical prediction AND a K5 conditional).","category":"empirical","confidence":0.78,"created":"2026-04-29T06:37:03+00:00"}
{"id": "c52_003", "pattern": "TRACK B CEILING CONDITIONS (0.87). Track B band [0.72-0.87]. Current highest: SI #39 KCRIT at 0.84. Theorem confidence bounded by min(premise_confidence, derivation_soundness). Premise chain: K1 (~0.90 definitional), K3 (~0.80 D4), K4 (~0.77 D4), K6 (~0.80 D4), K5 (~0.75 D3 empirical). Chain weakness: K5 is D3 \u2014 theorems requiring K5 premise are ceilinged at ~0.75-0.78. K5-independent theorems using K1+K3+K6 can approach higher ceiling. CONDITIONS FOR 0.87 APPROACH: (1) all premises at 0.85+; (2) derivation soundness independently verified; (3) domain-generality confirmed 2+ structural domains; (4) zero retraction candidates 5+ cycles. CURRENT STATUS: Track B ceiling 0.87 is unoccupied. Reachable only for theorems derived primarily from K1 (definitional ~0.90) + K6 (game-theoretic ~0.80), without K3/K4/K5 empirical content. CANDIDATE PATH: theorem that K1 alone implies structural assessment conclusion without K3/K4/K5 not yet formalized; C53+ target. GCRSC (SI #36) current ceiling: 0.82-0.85 if SI #35 premises verified at 0.85+. KCRIT (0.84) approaches ceiling because it is a claim about framework structure (topological/logical/prescriptive), not K5 empirical truth \u2014 structural verification by inspection possible. KEY INSIGHT: Track B ceiling elevation requires either (a) new theorems from K1-only/K6-only premise chains, or (b) K3/K4 confidence elevation above 0.85.", "category": "epistemology", "confidence": 0.75, "created": "2026-04-29T06:37:03+00:00"}
